Requirement Description

Fig4A, a good-looking cluster map

https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007%2Fs00497-018-00357-2 fromhttps://link.springer.com/article/10.1007%2Fs00497-018-00357-2

Fig. 4 Covariance clustering of expressed genes across the embryo time series. a Average maximum-normalized expression values for all genes in each of the 24 clusters generated by Mclust. Numbers in each panel indicate the number of genes grouped in that cluster, and polygons represents 1 standard deviation.

/cluster

FigureYa16fittingFigureYa94STEMboxFigureYa98STEMheatmap

Application Scenarios

This curve method is well suited to display data at multiple time points, such as multiple developmental periods, multiple time points after biological/non-stress treatment, etc. You can see at a glance the variation of gene expression in each cluster over time.

For more time series data results, see FigureYa16fitting, FigureYa94STEMbox, and FigureYa98STEMheatmap.

Download the GSE121236_RAW.tar archive from the GEO database of NCBI and https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/geo/query/acc.cgi?acc=GSE121236

files <- untar(tarfile = "GSE121236_RAW.tar", list = T)
temp_dir <- tempdir()
untar(tarfile =  "GSE121236_RAW.tar", exdir = temp_dir)

samples <- paste0(rep(c("pg", "gl", "eh", "lh", "et", "lt", "bc", "mg"), each = 3), "_", 1:3)
files_used <- paste0("GSM34282", 48:71, "_", samples, ".kallisto.tsv.gz")
files_used <- gsub("_bc_([123]).kallisto", "_bc_\\1.5ng.kallisto", files_used)

# GSE121236_RAW.tar

tpm <- lapply(files_used, function(i) {
  read.table(file = gzfile(description = file.path(temp_dir, i)), header = T) %$%
    tapply(tpm, INDEX = gsub("\\..*", "", target_id), sum) 
  #  Gene-level transcripts per million (TPM) were estimated by combining the TPM of all isoforms of protein-coding genes
}) %>% do.call(what = cbind)

colnames(tpm) <- samples

mclust

original textTo examine temporal changes in gene expression, proteincoding genes detected at 1 TPM in at least one embryonic stage of the Smart-seq2 time series were subjected to model-based clustering by Mclust [(Scrucca et al.2016), see Materials and methods]. Mclust classifies points according to a set of Gaussian mixture models and chooses the optimal model parameters to maximize the Bayesian information criterion (BIC). The mean TPM of 18,600 genes were converted to z-scores, and based on analysis with Mclust, the optimal cluster number was 24 (Online Fig. S5).

#tpm <- read.csv("easy_input.csv", row.names = 1)
# 
# Calculate the mean for each group, which corresponds to each developmental stage
tpm_mean <- apply(tpm, 1, function(x) {
  tapply(x, substr(colnames(tpm), 1, 2), mean)
}) %>% t

#  1 TPM in at least one embryonic stage
# Screen genes  1 TPM in at least one embryonic stage
genes_used <- which(rowSums(tpm_mean > 1) >= 1) %>% names()
# converted to z-scores
tpm_mean_scaled <- tpm_mean %>% t %>% scale() %>% t

# 
# Find the right number of clusters
bic <- mclustBIC(
  data = na.omit(tpm_mean_scaled[genes_used[1:2000],]),
  modelNames = "VVI", # I can not achieve valid results using VVV, which might be due to different versions of Mclust package (different internal settings?).
  G = seq(2,50,by=2))
plot(bic) # clusternumbers of components  MclustG # Drawing, which is used to select the appropriate number of clusters, i.e. abscissa numbers of components, is used to set the parameter G in the following Mclust function

# mclust
cluster <- Mclust(
  data = na.omit(tpm_mean_scaled[genes_used[1:2000],]), 
  G = 24, # 24cluster # This is the same as the original text, divided into 24 clusters
  modelNames = "VVI",
  prior = priorControl()
)

ggplot2

Start drawing

Use ggplot2 to mimic the graph in the article.

# 
# Organize into the format you need to paint
ggData <- cbind(tpm_mean_scaled[cluster$classification %>% names, ], cluster = cluster$classification) %>%
  as.data.frame() %>%
  rownames_to_column("gene") %>%
  gather(key = "stage", value = "zscore", -gene, -cluster,) %>%
  group_by(gene) %>%
  mutate(normalized = scales::rescale(zscore)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(stage = factor(stage, c("pg", "gl", "eh", "lh", "et", "lt", "bc", "mg"))) %>%
  group_by(stage, cluster) %>%
  summarise(
    mean = mean(normalized),
    sd = sd(normalized))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'stage'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
# 
# Set the colors of the three areas
fill_colors <- RColorBrewer::brewer.pal(6, "Set2")[c(4,6,5)]

ggplot(mapping = aes(x = stage, y = mean, group = cluster),
        data = ggData) + 
  # 
  # Fill the three areas of the background color
  ggnewscale::new_scale_fill() +
  annotate(geom = "rect", xmin = 0, xmax = 2.5, ymin = 0, ymax = 1, 
           fill = fill_colors[1], alpha = 0.6) +
  annotate(geom = "rect", xmin = 2.5, xmax = 7.5, ymin = 0, ymax = 1, 
           fill = fill_colors[2], alpha = 0.6) +
  annotate(geom = "rect", xmin = 7.5, xmax = 9.5, ymin = 0, ymax = 1,
           fill = fill_colors[3], alpha = 0.6) +
  
  # 
  # White standard deviation area
  geom_polygon(
    mapping = aes(stage, polygon, group = cluster),
    data = rbind(ggData %>% mutate(polygon = mean + sd) %>% arrange(stage, cluster) %>% select(stage, cluster, polygon),
                 ggData %>% mutate(polygon = mean - sd) %>% arrange(desc(stage), cluster) %>% select(stage, cluster, polygon)),
    fill = "white", alpha = 0.8) +
  
  # 
  # Draw lines
  geom_line(size = 1.2) +  #  # The thickness of the line
  facet_wrap(~cluster, nrow = 4) + # 4 # Draw in 4 lines
  theme_test()
## Warning: Using `size` aesthetic for lines was deprecated in ggplot2 3.4.0.
